g the consonants of the Semitic languages are very straightforward for a family of its time depth. Sound shifts affecting the vowels are more numerous and, at times, less regular.\n\n===Consonants===\nEach Proto-Semitic phoneme was reconstructed to explain a certain regular sound correspondence between various Semitic languages. Note that Latin letter values (''italicized'') for extinct languages are a question of transcription; the exact pronunciation is not recorded.\n\nMost of the attested languages have merged a number of the reconstructed original fricatives, though South Arabian retains all fourteen (and has added a fifteenth from *p > f).\n\nIn Aramaic and Hebrew, all non-emphatic stops occurring singly after a vowel were softened to fricatives, leading to an alternation that was often later phonemicized as a result of the loss of gemination.\n\nIn languages exhibiting pharyngealization of emphatics, the original velar emphatic has rather developed to a [[Uvular consonant|uvular]] stop {{IPA|[q]}}.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"vertical-align: middle; text-align: center;\"\n|+ Regular correspondences of the Proto-Semitic consonants<ref name=\"Kogan2012\" />\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Proto<br/>Semitic\n! rowspan=\"2\" | IPA\n! colspan=\"4\" | [[Arabic]]\n! rowspan=\"34\" |\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[Akkadian language|Akkadian]]\n! colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[Ugaritic language|Ugaritic]]\n! colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[Phoenician language|Phoenician]]\n! rowspan=\"34\" |\n! colspan=\"4\" | [[Hebrew]]\n! rowspan=\"34\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[Aramaic language|Aramaic]]\n! colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[Ge'ez language|Ge'ez]]\n|-\n! style=\"font-size:85%\" colspan=\"2\" | written\n! style=\"font-size:85%\"| [[Classical Arabic|Classical]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.kamal-osman.com/wp-content/uploads/The-Phonolgy-and-Morphology-of-Arabic-watson.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160301132237/http://www.kamal-osman.com/wp-content/uploads/The-Phonolgy-and-Morphology-of-Arabic-watson.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=2016-03-01|title=The Phonology and Morphology of Arabic|last=Watson|first=Janet|publisher=New York: Oxford University Press|year=2002|pages=13}}</ref>\n! style=\"font-size:85%\" | [[Modern Standard Arabic|Modern<br />Standard]]\n! style=\"font-size:85%\" colspan=\"2\" | written\n! style=\"font-size:85%\" | [[Tiberian Hebrew|Tiberian]]\n! style=\"font-size:85%\" | [[Modern Hebrew|Modern]]\n|-\n! {{transl|sem|[[Bet (letter)|*b]]}}\n! {{IPAblink|b}}\n| <big>\u0628</big>\n| ''{{transl|sem|b}}''\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|/b/}}\n| ''{{transl|sem|b}}''\n| \ud800\udf81 || ''{{transl|sem|b}}''\n| [[File:phoenician beth.svg|16px]] || ''{{transl|sem|b}}''\n| <big>{{script|Hebr|\u05d1}}</big> || {{transl|sem|\u1e07}}/{{transl|sem|b}}<sup>5</sup>\n| {{IPA|/v/, /b/}}\n| {{IPA|/v/, /b/}}\n| \u0712 \u05d1 || {{transl|sem|\u1e07}}/{{transl|sem|b}}<sup>5</sup>\n| \u1260 || {{IPA|/b/}}\n|-\n! {{transl|sem|[[Dalet|*d]]}}\n! {{IPAblink|d}}\n| <big>\u062f</big>\n| ''{{transl|sem|d}}''\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|/d/}}\n| ''{{transl|sem|d}}''\n| \ud800\udf84 || ''{{transl|sem|d}}''\n| [[File:phoenician daleth.svg|16px]] || ''{{transl|sem|d}}''\n| <big>{{script|Hebr|\u05d3}}</big> || {{transl|sem|\u1e0f}}/{{transl|sem|d}}<sup>5</sup>\n| {{IPA|/\u00f0/, /d/}}\n| {{IPA|/d/}}\n| \u0715 \u05d3 || {{transl|sem|\u1e0f}}/{{transl|sem|d}}<sup>5</sup>\n| \u12f0 || {{IPA|/d/}}\n|-\n! {{transl|sem|[[Gimel|*g]]}}\n! {{IPAblink|\u0261}}\n| <big>\u062c</big>\n| ''{{transl|sem|\u01e7}}''\n| {{IPA|/\u025f ~ d\u0361\u0292/}}<sup>9</sup>\n| {{IPA|/d\u0361\u0292/}}<sup>11</sup>\n| ''{{transl|sem|g}}''\n| \ud800\udf82 || ''{{transl|sem|g}}''\n| [[File:phoenician gimel.svg|16px]] || ''{{transl|sem|g}}''\n| <big>{{script|Hebr|\u05d2}}</big> || {{transl|sem|\u1e21}}/{{transl|sem|g}}<sup>5</sup>\n| {{IPA|/\u0263/, /g/}}\n| {{IPA|/\u0261/}}\n| \u0713 \u05d2 || {{transl|sem|\u1e21}}/{{transl|sem|g}}<sup>5</sup>\n| \u1308 || {{IPA|/\u0261/}}\n|