g to write\"\n\nand the same root in Hebrew:\n(A line under k and b mean a fricitive, x for k and v for b.)\n\n:'''''k'''\u0101'''\u1e6f'''a'''\u1e07'''ti'' \u05db\u05ea\u05d1\u05ea\u05d9 \"I wrote\"\n:'''''k'''\u0101'''\u1e6f'''a'''\u1e07'''t\u0101'' \u05db\u05ea\u05d1\u05ea \"you (''m'') wrote\"\n:'''''k'''\u0101'''\u1e6f'''a'''\u1e07'''t'' \u05db\u05ea\u05d1\u05ea \"you (''f'') wrote\"\n:'''''k'''\u0101'''\u1e6f'''a'''\u1e07'''nu'' \u05db\u05ea\u05d1\u05e0\u05d5 \"we wrote\"\n:'''''k'''\u0101'''\u1e6f'''\u1e07'''u'' \u05db\u05ea\u05d1\u05d5 \"they wrote\"\n:'''''k'''\u0101'''\u1e6f'''a'''\u1e07'' \u05db\u05ea\u05d1 \"he wrote\"\n:'''''k'''\u0101'''\u1e6f'''\u1e07'''a'' \u05db\u05ea\u05d1 \"she wrote\"\n:'''''k'''a'''tt'''\u0101'''\u1e07''''' \u05db\u05ea\u05d1 \"reporter\" (''m'')\n:'''''k'''a'''tt'''e'''\u1e07'''e\u1e6f'' \u05db\u05ea\u05d1\u05ea \"reporter\" (''f'')\n:'''''k'''a'''tt'''\u0101'''\u1e07'''\u0101'' \u05db\u05ea\u05d1\u05d4 \"article\" (plural '''''k'''a'''tt'''\u0101'''\u1e07'''\u014d\u1e6f'' \u05db\u05ea\u05d1\u05d5\u05ea)\n:''mi'''\u1e35t'''\u0101'''\u1e07''''' \u05de\u05db\u05ea\u05d1 \"postal letter\" (plural ''mi'''\u1e35t'''\u0101'''\u1e07'''\u012bm'' \u05de\u05db\u05ea\u05d1\u05d9\u05dd)\n:''mi'''\u1e35t'''\u0101'''\u1e07'''\u0101'' \u05de\u05db\u05ea\u05d1\u05d4 \"writing desk\" (plural ''mi'''\u1e35t'''\u0101'''\u1e07'''\u014d\u1e6f'' \u05de\u05db\u05ea\u05d1\u05d5\u05ea)\n:'''''k'''\u0259'''\u1e6f'''\u014d'''\u1e07'''e\u1e6f'' \u05db\u05ea\u05d5\u05d1\u05ea \"address\" (plural '''''k'''\u0259'''\u1e6f'''\u014d'''\u1e07'''\u014d\u1e6f'' \u05db\u05ea\u05d5\u05d1\u05d5\u05ea)\n:'''''k'''\u0259'''\u1e6f'''\u0101'''\u1e07''''' \u05db\u05ea\u05d1 \"handwriting\"\n:'''''k'''\u0101'''\u1e6f'''\u016b'''\u1e07''''' \u05db\u05ea\u05d5\u05d1 \"written\" (''f'' '''''k'''\u0259'''\u1e6f'''\u016b'''\u1e07'''\u0101'' \u05db\u05ea\u05d5\u05d1\u05d4)\n:''hi'''\u1e35t'''\u012b'''\u1e07''''' \u05d4\u05db\u05ea\u05d9\u05d1 \"he dictated\" (''f'' ''hi'''\u1e35t'''\u012b'''\u1e07'''\u0101'' \u05d4\u05db\u05ea\u05d9\u05d1\u05d4)\n:''hi\u1e6f'''k'''a'''tt'''\u0113'''\u1e07''''' \u05d4\u05ea\u05db\u05ea\u05d1 \"he corresponded (''f'' ''hi\u1e6f'''k'''a'''tt'''\u0259'''\u1e07'''\u0101'' \u05d4\u05ea\u05db\u05ea\u05d1\u05d4)\n:''ni'''\u1e35t'''a'''\u1e07''''' \u05e0\u05db\u05ea\u05d1 \"it was written\" (''m'')\n:''ni'''\u1e35t'''\u0259'''\u1e07'''\u0101'' \u05e0\u05db\u05ea\u05d1\u05d4 \"it was written\" (''f'')\n:'''''k'''\u0259'''\u1e6f'''\u012b'''\u1e07''''' \u05db\u05ea\u05d9\u05d1 \"spelling\" (''m'')\n:''ta'''\u1e35t'''\u012b'''\u1e07''''' \u05ea\u05db\u05ea\u05d9\u05d1 \"prescript\" (''m'')\n:''m'''\u0259''''''\u1e35'''u'''tt'''\u0101'''\u1e07''''' \u05de\u05db\u05d5\u05ea\u05d1 \"addressee\" (''me'''\u1e35'''u'''tt'''e'''\u1e07'''e\u1e6f'' \u05de\u05db\u05d5\u05ea\u05d1\u05ea ''f'')\n:'''''k'''\u0259'''\u1e6f'''u'''bb'''\u0101'' \u05db\u05ea\u05d5\u05d1\u05d4 \"ketubah (a Jewish marriage contract)\" (''f'')\n\nIn Tigrinya and Amharic, this root survives only in the noun ''kitab'', meaning \"amulet\", and the verb \"to vaccinate\". Ethiopic-derived languages use different roots for things that have to do with writing (and in some cases counting) primitive root: \u1e63-f and trilateral root stems: m-\u1e63-f, \u1e63-h-f, and \u1e63-f-r are used. This roots also exists in other Semitic languages like (Hebrew: ''sep\u0304er'' \"book\", ''[[sofer|s\u014dp\u0304er]]'' \"scribe\", ''misp\u0101r'' \"number\" and ''sipp\u016br'' \"story\"). (this root also exists in Arabic and is used to form words with a close meaning to \"writing\", such as ''\u1e63a\u1e25\u0101fa'' \"journalism\", and ''\u1e63a\u1e25\u012bfa'' \"newspaper\" or \"parchment\").\nVerbs in other non-Semitic Afroasiatic languages show similar radical patterns, but more usually with biconsonantal roots; e.g. [[Kabyle language|Kabyle]] ''afeg'' means \"fly!\", while ''affug'' means \"flight\", and ''yufeg'' means \"he flew\" (compare with Hebrew, where ''hap\u0304l\u0113\u1e21'' means \"set sail!\", ''hap\u0304l\u0101\u1e21\u0101'' means \"a sailing trip\", and ''hip\u0304l\u012b\u1e21'' means \"he sailed\", while the unrelated ''\u0295\u016bp\u0304'', ''t\u0259\u0295\u016bp\u0304\u0101'' and ''\u0295\u0101p\u0304'' pertain to flight).\n\n===Independent personal pronouns===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" | English\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[Proto-Semitic]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[Akkadian language|Akkadian]]\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Arabic language|Arabic]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[Ge'ez language|Ge'ez]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[Aramaic language|Aramaic]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[Assyrian Neo-Aramaic|Assyrian]]\n|-\n! [[Modern Standard Arabic|standard]]\n! [[varieties of Arabic|vernaculars]]\n|-\n| I\n| {{transl|sem|*\u0294an\u0101ku,<ref group=\"nb\">While some believe that *\u0294an\u0101ku was an innovation in some branches of Semitic utilizing an \"intensifying\" *-ku, comparison to other Afro-Asiatic 1ps pronouns (e.g. Eg. ''3nk'', Coptic ''anak'', ''anok'', [[proto-Berber language|proto-Berber]] *\u0259nakk\u02b7) suggests that this goes further back. (Dolgopolsky 1999, pp. 10\u201311.)</ref> *\u0294aniya}}\n| {{transl|sem|an\u0101ku}}\n| \u0623\u0646\u0627 {{transl|sem|\u0294an\u0101}}\n| {{transl|sem|\u0294an\u0101}}, an\u0101, {{transl|sem|ana, \u0101ni, \u0101na, \u0101nig}}\n| {{transl|sem|\u0294ana}}\n| \u05d0\u05e0\u05db\u05d9, \u05d0\u05e0\u05d9 {{transl|sem|\u0294\u0101n\u014d\u1e35\u012b, \u0294\u0103n\u012b}}\n| \u05d0\u05e0\u05d0 {{transl|sem|\u0294an\u0101}}\n| {{transl|sem|\u0101n\u0101}}\n|-\n| You (sg., masc.)\n| {{transl|sem|*\u0294anka > *\u0294anta}}\n| {{transl|sem|atta}}\n| \u0623\u0646\u062a {{transl|sem|\u0294anta}}\n| {{transl|sem|\u0294ant}}, ant, inta, inte, inti, int, (i)nta\n| {{transl|sem|\u0294\u00e1nta}}\n| \u05d0\u05ea\u05d4 {{transl|sem|\u0294att\u0101}}\n| \u05d0\u05e0\u05ea {{transl|sem|\u0294ant\u0101}}\n| {{transl|sem|\u0101t}}, {{transl|sem|\u0101ty}}, {{transl|sem|\u0101ten}}\n|-\n| You (sg., fem.)\n| {{transl|sem|*\u0294anti}}\n| {{transl|sem|atti}}\n| \u0623\u0646\u062a {{transl|sem|\u0294anti}}\n| \u0294anti, anti, {{transl|sem|inti, init}} (i)nti, intch\n| {{transl|sem|\u0294\u00e1nti}}\n| \u05d0\u05ea {{transl|sem|\u0294att}}\n| \u05d0\u05e0\u05ea {{transl|sem|\u0294anti}}\n| {{transl|sem|\u0101t}}, {{transl|sem|\u0101ty}}, {{transl|sem|\u0101ten}}\n|-\n| He\n| {{transl|sem|*su\u0294a}}\n| {{transl|sem|\u0161\u016b}}\n| \u0647\u0648 {{transl|sem|huwa}}, h\u016b\n| {{transl|sem|huwwa, huwwe}}, h\u016b\n| {{transl|sem|w\u0259\u0294\u0259tu}}\n| \u05d4\u05d5\u05d0 {{transl|sem|h\u016b}}\n| \u05d4\u05d5\u05d0 {{transl|sem|hu}}\n| {{transl|sem|ow\u0101}}\n|-\n| She\n| {{transl|sem|*si\u0294a}}\n| {{transl|sem|\u0161\u012b}}\n| \u0647\u064a {{transl|sem|hiya}}, h\u012b\n| {{transl|sem|hiyya, hiyye}}, h\u012b\n| {{transl|sem|y\u0259\u0294\u0259ti}}\n| \u05d4\u05d9\u05d0 {{transl|sem|h\u012b}}\n| \u05d4\u05d9\u05d0 {{transl|sem|hi}}\n| {{transl|sem|ay\u0101}}\n|-\n| We\n| {{transl|sem|*niya\u0127n\u016b, *niya\u0127n\u0101}}\n| {{transl|sem|n\u012bnu}}\n| \u0646\u062d\u0646 {{transl|sem|na\u0127nu}}\n| ni\u0127na, i\u0127na, \u0127inna\n| {{transl|sem|n\u0259\u0127n\u0101}}\n| \u05d0\u05e0\u05d5, \u05d0\u05e0\u05d7\u05e0\u05d5 {{transl|sem|\u0294\u0101n\u016b, \u0294\u0103na\u0127n\u016b}}\n| \u05e0\u05d7\u05e0\u05d0 {{transl|sem|n\u00e1\u0127n\u0101}}\n| {{transl|sem|axnan}}\n|-\n| Ye (dual)\n| {{transl|sem|*\u0294antun\u0101}}\n| \n| \u0623\u0646\u062a\u0645\u0627 {{transl|sem|\u0294antum\u0101}}\n|Plural form is used\n| \n| <!-- does not exist -->\n| \n|-\n| They (dual)\n| {{transl|sem|*sun\u0101<ref group=\"nb\">The Akkadian form is from Sargonic Akkadian. Among the Semitic languages, there are languages with /i/ as the final vowel (this is the form in Mehri). For a recent discussion concerning the reconstruction of the forms of the dual pronouns, see Bar-Asher, Elitzur. 2009. \"Dual Pronouns in Semitics and an Evaluation of the Evidence for their Existence in Biblical Hebrew,\" Ancient Near Eastern Studies 46: 32\u201349</ref>}}\n| {{transl|sem|*sun\u012b(ti)}}\n| \u0647\u0645\u0627 {{transl|sem|hum\u0101}}\n|Plural form is used\n| \n| \n| \n|-\n| Ye (pl., masc.)\n| {{transl|sem|*\u0294antun\u016b}}\n| {{transl|sem|attunu}}\n| \u0623\u0646\u062a\u0645 {{transl|sem|\u0294antum}}, {{transl|sem|\u0294antumu}}\n| {{transl|sem|\u0294antum}}, antum, antu, {{transl|sem|intu, intum}}, (i)nt\u016bma\n| {{transl|sem|\u0294ant\u0259mu}}\n| \u05d0\u05ea\u05dd {{transl|sem|\u0294attem}}\n| \u05d0\u05e0\u05ea\u05df {{transl|sem|\u0294antun}}\n| | {{transl|sem|axt\u014dx\u016bn}}\n|-\n| Ye (pl., fem.)\n| {{transl|sem|*\u0294antin\u0101}}\n| {{transl|sem|attina}}\n| \u0623\u0646\u062a\u0646\u0651 {{transl|sem|\u0294antunna}}<!--\n| {{transl|sem|}}-->\n|{{transl|sem|\u0294antin}}, antin, {{transl|sem|\u0294antum}}, antu, {{transl|sem|intu, intum}}, (i)nt\u016bma\n| {{transl|sem|\u0294ant\u0259n}}\n| \u05d0\u05ea\u05df {{transl|sem|\u0294atten}}\n| \u05d0\u05e0\u05ea\u05df {{transl|sem|\u0294anten}}\n| {{transl|sem|axt\u014dx\u016bn}}\n|-\n| They (masc.)\n| {{transl|sem|*sun\u016b}}\n| {{transl|sem|\u0161unu}}\n| \u0647\u0645 {{transl|sem|hum}}, {{transl|sem|humu}}\n| hum, {{transl|sem|humma}}, h\u016bma, hom, hinne(n)\n| {{transl|sem|\u0294\u0259muntu}}\n| \u05d4\u05dd, \u05d4\u05de\u05d4 {{transl|sem|h\u0113m, h\u0113mm\u0101}}\n| \u05d4\u05e0\u05df {{transl|sem|hinnun}}\n| {{transl|sem|eni}}\n|-\n| They (fem.)\n| {{transl|sem|*sin\u0101}}\n| {{transl|sem|\u0161ina}}\n| \u0647\u0646\u0651 {{transl|sem|hunna}}<!--\n| {{transl|sem|}}-->\n|hin, hinne(n), hum, humma, h\u016bma\n| {{transl|sem|\u0294\u0259m\u0101ntu}}\n| \u05d4\u05df, \u05d4\u05e0\u05d4   {{transl|sem|h\u0113n, h\u0113nn\u0101}}\n| \u05d4\u05e0\u05df {{transl|sem|hinnin}}\n| {{transl|sem|eni}}\n|-\n|}\n\n===Cardinal numerals===\n{{See also|List of numbers in various languages}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! English\n! Proto-Semitic<ref>Weninger, Stefan (2011). \"Reconstructive Morphology\". In ''Semitic languages: an international handbook,'' Stefan Weninger, ed. Berlin: Walter de Gruyter. P. 166.</ref>\n! IPA\n! Arabic\n! Hebrew\n! Tigrinya\n! [[Sabaean language|Sabaean]]\n! Assyrian Neo-Aramaic\n! Maltese\n|-\n| One\n| {{transl|sem|*\u02bca\u1e25ad-, *\u02bbi\u0161t-}}\n| {{IPA|\u0294a\u0127ad, \u0294i\u0283t}}\n| \u0648\u0627\u062d\u062f\u060c \u0623\u062d\u062f {{IPA|wa\u02d0\u0127id-, \u0294a\u0127ad-}}\n| \u05d0\u05d7\u05d3 {{transl|sem|\u02bce\u1e25\u00e1\u1e0f}}, {{IPA|\u0294e\u02c8\u03c7ad}}\n| {{IPA|\u0127ade}}\n| {{transl|sem|\u0294\u1e25d}}\n| {{transl|sem|x\u0101}}\n| wie\u0127ed\n|-\n| Two\n| {{transl|sem|*\u1e6fin-\u0101n}} (nom.), {{transl|sem|*\u1e6fin-ayn}} (obl.), {{transl|sem|*kil\u02bc-}}\n| {{IPA|\u03b8ina\u02d0n, \u03b8inajn, kil\u0294}}\n| \u0627\u062b\u0646\u0627\u0646 {{IPA|i\u03b8n-\u0101ni}} (nom.), \u0627\u062b\u0646\u064a\u0646 {{IPA|i\u03b8n-ajni}} (obj.), \u0627\u062b\u0646\u062a\u0627\u0646 fem. i\u03b8nat-\u0101ni, \u0627\u062b\u0646\u062a\u064a\u0646 i\u03b8nat-ajni\n| \u05e9\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd {{transl|sem|\u0161\u0259n\u00e1yim}} {{IPA|\u02c8\u0283n-ajim}}, fem. \u05e9\u05ea\u05d9\u05dd {{transl|sem|\u0161\u0259t\u00e1yim}} {{IPA|\u02c8\u0283t-ajim}}\n| {{IPA|kelete}}\n| {{transl|sem|*\u1e6fny}}\n| {{transl|sem|treh}}\n| tnejn\n|-\n| Three\n| {{transl|sem|*\u015bal\u0101\u1e6f-}} > {{transl|sem|*\u1e6fal\u0101\u1e6f-}}<ref group=\"nb\">{{citation|first=Edward|last=Lipi\u0144ski|title=Semitic languages: outline of a comparative grammar}}. This root underwent regressive assimilation. This parallels the non-adjacent assimilation of *\u015b... > *\u0161...\u0161 in proto-Canaanite or proto-North-West-Semitic in the roots *\u015bam?\u0161 > *\u0161am\u0161 'sun' and *\u015bur?\u0161 > *\u0161ur\u0161 'root'. (Dolgopolsky pp. 61\u201362.) The form ''{{transl|sem|*\u1e6fal\u0101\u1e6f-}}'' appears in most languages (e.g. Aramaic, Arabic, Ugaritic), but the original form {{transl|sem|\u015bl\u1e6f}} appears in the [[Old South Arabian]] languages, and a form with ''s'' < {{transl|sem|*\u015b}} (rather than ''\u0161'' < {{transl|sem|*\u1e6f}}) appears in [[Akkadian language|Akkadian]].</ref>\n| {{IPA|\u026cala\u02d0\u03b8 > \u03b8ala\u02d0\u03b8}}\n| \u062b\u0644\u0627\u062b {{IPA|\u03b8ala\u02d0\u03b8-}}\n| fem. \u05e9\u05dc\u05d5\u05e9 {{transl|sem|\u0161\u0101l\u1e53\u0161}} {{IPA|\u0283a\u02c8lo\u0283}}\n| {{IPA|seleste}} ([[Ge'ez language|Ge'ez]] ''\u015b\u00e4las'')\n| {{transl|sem|*\u015bl\u1e6f}}\n| {{transl|sem|\u1e6dl\u0101}}\n| tlieta\n|-\n| Four\n| {{transl|sem|*\u02bcarba\u02bb-}}\n| {{IPA|\u0294arba\u0295}}\n| \u0623\u0631\u0628\u0639 {{IPA|\u0294arba\u0295-}}\n| fem. \u05d0\u05e8\u05d1\u05e2 {{transl|sem|\u02bc\u00e1rba\u02bb}} {{IPA|\u02c8\u0294a\u0281ba}}\n| {{IPA|arba\u0295te}}\n| {{transl|sem|*\u02bcrb\u02bb}}\n| {{transl|sem|arp\u0101}}\n| erbg\u0127a\n|-\n| Five\n| {{transl|sem|*\u1e2bam\u0161-}}\n| {{IPA|\u03c7am\u0283}}\n| \u062e\u0645\u0633 {{IPA|\u03c7ams-}}\n| fem. \u05d7\u05de\u05e9 {{transl|sem|\u1e25\u0101\u0301m\u0113\u0161}} {{IPA|\u02c8\u03c7ame\u0283}}\n| {{IPA|\u0127amu\u0283te}}\n| {{transl|sem|*\u1e2bm\u0161}}\n| {{transl|sem|xam\u0161\u0101}}\n| \u0127amsa\n|-\n| Six\n| {{transl|sem|*\u0161id\u1e6f-}}<ref group=\"nb\">{{citation|first=Edward|last=Lipi\u0144ski|title=Semitic languages: outline of a comparative grammar}}. This root was also assimilated in various ways. For example, Hebrew reflects {{transl|sem|*\u0161i\u0161\u0161-}}, with total assimilation; Arabic reflects {{transl|sem|*\u0161itt-}} in cardinal numerals, but less assimilated {{transl|sem|*\u0161\u0101di\u0161-}} in ordinal numerals. [[Epigraphic South Arabian]] reflects original {{transl|sem|*\u0161d\u1e6f}}; Ugaritic has a form {{transl|sem|\u1e6f\u1e6f}}, in which the {{transl|sem|\u1e6f}} has been assimilated throughout the root.</ref>\n| {{IPA|\u0283id\u03b8}}\n| \u0633\u062a\u0651 {{IPA|sitt-}} (ordinal \u0633\u0627\u062f\u0633 {{IPA|sa\u02d0dis-}})\n| fem. \u05e9\u05e9 {{transl|sem|\u0161\u0113\u0161}} {{IPA|\u0283e\u0283}}\n| {{IPA|\u0283du\u0283te}}\n| {{transl|sem|*\u0161d\u1e6f/\u0161\u1e6f}}\n| {{transl|sem|\u00eb\u0161t\u0101}}\n| sitta\n|-\n| Seven\n| {{transl|sem|*\u0161ab\u02bb-}}\n| {{IPA|\u0283ab\u0295}}\n| \u0633\u0628\u0639 {{IPA|sab\u0295-}}\n| fem. \u05e9\u05d1\u05e2 {{transl|sem|\u0161\u00e9\u1e07a\u02bb}} {{IPA|\u02c8\u0283eva}}\n| {{IPA|\u0283ew\u0295ate}}\n| {{transl|sem|*\u0161b\u02bb}}\n| {{transl|sem|\u0161ow\u0101}}\n| sebg\u0127a\n|-\n| Eight\n| {{transl|sem|*\u1e6fam\u0101niy-}}\n| {{IPA|\u03b8ama\u02d0nij-}}\n| \u062b\u0645\u0627\u0646\u064a {{IPA|\u03b8ama\u02d0n-ij-}}\n| fem. \u05e9\u05de\u05d5\u05e0\u05d4 {{transl|sem|\u0161\u0259m\u1e53neh}} {{IPA|\u0283\u02c8mone}}\n| {{IPA|\u0283emonte}}\n| {{transl|sem|*\u1e6fmny/\u1e6fmn}}\n| {{transl|sem|*tmany\u0101}}\n| tmienja \n|-\n| Nine\n| {{transl|sem|*ti\u0161\u02bb-}}\n| {{IPA|ti\u0283\u0295}}\n| \u062a\u0633\u0639 {{IPA|tis\u0295-}}\n| fem. \u05ea\u05e9\u05e2 {{transl|sem|t\u1e17\u0161a\u02bb}} {{IPA|\u02c8tej\u0283a}}\n| {{IPA|t\u0283\u0295ate}}\n| {{transl|sem|*t\u0161\u02bb}}\n| {{transl|sem|*u\u010d\u0101}}\n| disg\u0127a\n|-\n| Ten\n| {{transl|sem|*\u02bba\u015br-}}\n| {{IPA|\u0295a\u026cr}}\n| \u0639\u0634\u0631 {{IPA|\u0295a\u0283(a)r-}}\n| fem. \u05e2\u05e9\u05e8 {{transl|sem|\u02bb\u00e9\u015ber}} {{IPA|\u02c8\u0294ese\u0281}}\n| {{IPA|\u0295aserte}}\n| {{transl|sem|*\u02bb\u015br}}\n| {{transl|sem|*u\u1e63r\u0101}}\n| g\u0127axra\n|-\n|}\nThese are the basic numeral stems without feminine suffixes. Note that in most older Semitic languages, the forms of the numerals from 3 to 10 exhibit gender polarity (also called \"chiastic concord\" or reverse agreement), i.e. if the counted noun is masculine, the numeral would be feminine and vice versa.\n\n===Typology===\nSome early Semitic languages are speculated to have had weak [[ergative-absolutive language|ergative]] features.<ref>{{cite journal| first=Hans-Peter |last=M\u00fcller |title=Ergative Constructions In Early Semitic Languages |journal=Journal of Near Eastern Studies |volume=54 |issue=4 |year=1995 |pages=261\u2013271 |jstor=545846 |doi=10.1086/373769}}.</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=The rise and fall of ergativity in Aramaic : cycles of alignment change|last=Coghill|first=Eleanor|isbn=9780198723806|edition= First |location=Oxford|oclc=962895347|year = 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Common vocabulary==\nDue to the Semitic languages' common origin, they share some words and roots. Others differ. For example:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=\"2\"\n! [[English language|English]]\n! Proto-Semitic\n! [[Akkadian language|Akkadian]]\n! [[Arabic]]\n! [[Aramaic language|Aramaic]]\n! [[Assyrian Neo-Aramaic|Assyrian]]\n! [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]]\n! [[Ge'ez language|Ge'ez]]\n! [[Mehri language|Mehri]]\n! [[Maltese language|Maltese]]\n|-\n| father\n| {{transl|sem|*\u02bcab-}}\n| {{transl|sem|''ab-''}}\n| {{transl|sem|\u02bcab-}}\n| {{transl|sem|\u02bca\u1e07-\u0101\u02bc}}\n| {{transl|sem|b\u0101b\u0101}}\n| {{transl|sem|\u02bc\u0101\u1e07}}\n| {{transl|sem|\u02bcab}}\n| {{transl|sem|\u1e25a-yb}}\n| {{transl|sem|bu}}, ({{transl|sem|missier}})\n|-\n| heart\n| {{transl|sem|*lib(a)b-}}\n| {{transl|sem|libb-}}\n| {{transl|sem|lubb-}}, ({{transl|sem|qalb-}})\n| {{transl|sem|lebb-\u0101\u02bc}}\n| {{transl|sem|l\u00ebb\u0101}}\n| {{transl|sem|l\u00eb\u1e07, l\u00eb\u1e07\u0101\u1e07}}\n| {{transl|sem|libb}}\n| {{transl|sem|\u1e25a-wb\u0113b}}\n| {{transl|sem|ilbieba}}, ({{transl|sem|qalb}})\n|-\n| house\n| {{transl|sem|*bayt-}}\n| {{transl|sem|b\u012btu, b\u0113tu}}\n| {{transl|sem|bayt-}}, ({{transl|sem|d\u0101r-}})\n| {{transl|sem|bayt-\u0101\u02bc}}\n| {{transl|sem|b\u0113t\u0101}}\n| {{transl|sem|b\u00e1yi\u1e6f}}\n| {{transl|sem|bet}}\n| {{transl|sem|beyt, b\u00eat}}\n| {{transl|sem|bejt}}, ({{transl|sem|dar}})\n|-\n| peace\n| {{transl|sem|*\u0161al\u0101m-}}\n| {{transl|sem|\u0161al\u0101m-}}\n| {{transl|sem|sal\u0101m-}}\n| {{transl|sem|\u0161l\u0101m-\u0101\u02bc}}\n| {{transl|sem|\u0161l\u0101m\u0101}}\n| {{transl|sem|\u0161\u0101l\u00f4m}}\n| {{transl|sem|sal\u0101m}}\n| {{transl|sem|s\u0259l\u014dm}}\n| {{transl|sem|sliem}}\n|-\n| tongue\n| {{transl|sem|*li\u0161\u0101n-/*la\u0161\u0101n-}}\n| {{transl|sem|li\u0161\u0101n-}}\n| {{transl|sem|lis\u0101n-}}\n| {{transl|sem|le\u0161\u0161\u0101n-\u0101\u02bc}}\n| {{transl|sem|li\u0161\u0101n\u0101}}\n| {{transl|sem|l\u0101\u0161\u00f4n}}\n| {{transl|sem|liss\u0101n}}\n| {{transl|sem|\u0259w\u0161\u0113n}}\n| {{transl|sem|ilsien}}\n|-\n| water\n| {{transl|sem|*may-/*m\u0101y-}}\n| {{transl|sem|m\u00fb (root *m\u0101-/*m\u0101y-)}}\n| {{transl|sem|m\u0101\u02bc-/m\u0101y}}\n| {{transl|sem|mayy-\u0101\u02bc}}\n| {{transl|sem|m\u0113y\u0101}}\n| {{transl|sem|m\u00e1yim}}\n| {{transl|sem|m\u0101y}}\n| {{transl|sem|\u1e25\u0259-m\u014d}}\n| {{transl|sem|ilma}}\n|}\n\nTerms given in brackets are not derived from the respective Proto-Semitic roots, though they may also derive from Proto-Semitic (as does e.g. Arabic ''d\u0101r'', cf. Biblical Hebrew ''d\u014dr'' \"dwelling\").\n\nSometimes, certain roots differ in meaning from one Semitic language to another. For example, the root ''b-y-\u1e0d'' in Arabic has the meaning of \"white\" as well as \"egg\", whereas in Hebrew it only means \"egg\". The root ''l-b-n'' means \"milk\" in Arabic, but the color \"white\" in Hebrew. The root ''l-\u1e25-m'' means \"meat\" in Arabic, but \"bread\" in Hebrew and \"cow\" in Ethiopian Semitic; the original meaning was most probably \"food\". The word ''medina'' (root: m-d-n) has the meaning of \"metropolis\" in Amharic, \"city\" in Arabic and Ancient Hebrew, and \"State\" in Modern Hebrew.\n\nOf course, there is sometimes no relation between the roots. For example, \"knowledge\" is represented in Hebrew by the root ''y-d-\u02bf'', but in Arabic by the roots ''\u02bf-r-f'' and ''\u02bf-l-m'' and in Ethiosemitic by the roots ''\u02bf-w-q'' and ''f-l-\u1e6d''.\n\nFor more comparative vocabulary lists, see Wiktionary appendices:\n\n* [http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/Appendix:List_of_Proto-Semitic_stems List of Proto-Semitic stems]\n* [http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/Appendix:Swadesh_lists_for_Afro-Asiatic_languages Swadesh lists for Afro-Asiatic languages]\n\n==Classification==\nThere are six fairly uncontroversial nodes within the Semitic languages: [[East Semitic languages|East Semitic]], [[Northwest Semitic languages|Northwest Semitic]], [[Arabic languages|North Arabian]], [[Old South Arabian]] (also known as Sayhadic), [[Modern South Arabian languages|Modern South Arabian]], and [[Ethiopian Semitic languages|Ethiopian Semitic]]. These are generally grouped further, but there is ongoing debate as to which belong together. The classification based on shared innovations given below, established by [[Robert Hetzron]] in 1976 and with later emendations by John Huehnergard and Rodgers as summarized in Hetzron 1997, is the most widely accepted today. In particular, several Semiticists still argue for the traditional (partially nonlinguistic) view of Arabic as part of South Semitic, and a few (e.g. Alexander Militarev or the German-Egyptian professor Arafa Hussein Mustafa{{Citation needed|date=October 2008}}) see the South Arabian languages{{clarify|date=September 2011}} as a third branch of Semitic alongside East and West Semitic, rather than as a subgroup of South Semitic. However, a new classification groups Old South Arabian as Central Semitic instead.<ref>{{cite book |last=Hackett |first=Jo Ann |year=2006 |chapter=Semitic languages |editor1=Keith Brown |editor2=Sarah Ogilvie |pages=929\u2013935 |chapter-url=https://books.google.de/books?id=F2SRqDzB50wC&pg=PA931 |title=Concise Encyclopedia of Languages of the World |publisher=Elsevier |accessdate=2 June 2019 |via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Blench]] notes{{citation needed|date=April 2015}} that the [[Gurage languages]] are highly divergent and wonders whether they might not be a primary branch, reflecting an origin of Afroasiatic in or near Ethiopia. At a lower level, there is still no general agreement on where to draw the line between \"languages\" and \"dialects\"{{snd}} an issue particularly relevant in Arabic, Aramaic, and Gurage{{snd}} and the strong mutual influences between Arabic dialects render a genetic subclassification of them particularly difficult.\n\nA [[computational phylogenetic]] analysis by Kitchen, et al. (2009)<ref>Andrew Kitchen, Christopher Ehret, Shiferaw Assefa, Connie J. Mulligan (2009). [http://rspb.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/276/1668/2703 Bayesian phylogenetic analysis of Semitic languages identifies an Early Bronze Age origin of Semitic in the Near East]. Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences 276(1668), 2703-2710. {{doi|10.1098/rspb.2009.0408}}</ref> considers the Semitic languages to have originated in the [[Levant]] about 5,750 years ago during the Early [[Bronze Age]], with early Ethiosemitic originating from southern Arabia approximately 2,800 years ago.\n\nThe [[Himyaritic language|Himyaritic]] and [[Sutean language]]s appear to have been Semitic, but are unclassified due to insufficient data.\n\n* [[East Semitic languages|East Semitic]]\n* [[West Semitic languages|West Semitic]]\n** [[Central Semitic languages|Central Semitic]]\n*** [[Northwest Semitic languages|Northwest Semitic]]\n*** [[Arabic languages|Arabic]]\n** [[South Semitic languages|South Semitic]]\n*** Western: [[Ethiopian Semitic languages|Ethiopian Semitic]] and [[Old South Arabian]]\n*** Eastern: [[Modern South Arabian languages|Modern South Arabian]]\n\n==Semitic-speaking peoples==\nThe following is a list of some modern and [[ancient Semitic-speaking peoples]] and nations:\n\n===Central Semitic===\n* [[Ammonite language|Ammonite speakers]] of [[Ammon]]\n* [[Amorites]]{{snd}} 20th century BC\n* [[Arabs]]\n* [[Ancient North Arabian]]-speaking [[bedouin]]s\n* [[Arameans]]{{snd}} 16th to 8th centuries BC<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/32018/Aramaean |title=Aramaean \u2013 Britannica Online Encyclopedia |encyclopedia=Britannica.com |accessdate=2013-01-27}}</ref> / [[Akhlame]]s (Ahlamu) 14th century BC.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|url=http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-9005278/Akhlame |title=Akhlame \u2013 Britannica Online Encyclopedia |encyclopedia=Britannica.com |accessdate=2013-01-27}}</ref>\n* [[Canaanite languages|Canaanite-speaking]] nations of the early Iron Age:\n* [[Chaldea]] {{snd}} appeared in southern Mesopotamia c. 1000 BC and eventually disappeared into the general Babylonian population.\n* [[Edom]]ites\n* [[Hebrews]]/[[Israelites]]{{snd}} founded the nation of [[History of ancient Israel and Judah|Israel]] which later split into the Kingdoms of [[Kingdom of Israel (Samaria)|Israel]] and [[Kingdom of Judah|Judah]]. The remnants of these people became the [[Jews]] and the [[Samaritans]].\n* [[Maltese people|Maltese]]\n* [[Mandaeans]]\n* [[Moab]]\n* [[Nabataeans]]\n* [[Phoenicia]]{{snd}} founded Mediterranean colonies including [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]], [[Sidon]] and [[ancient Carthage]]. The remnants of these people became the modern inhabitants of Lebanon.\n* [[Ugarit]], 14th to 12th centuries BC\n* [[Nasrani (Arabic term for Christian)|Nasrani]] (Syrian Christian)\n\n===East Semitic===\n* [[Akkadian Empire]]{{snd}} ancient Semitic speakers moved into Mesopotamia in the fourth millennium BC and settled among the local peoples of [[Sumer]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|url=http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-9110693/Mesopotamian-religion |title=Mesopotamian religion \u2013 Britannica Online Encyclopedia |encyclopedia=Britannica.com |accessdate=2013-01-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia|url=http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-9005290/Akkadian-language#62711.hook |title=Akkadian language \u2013 Britannica Online Encyclopedia |encyclopedia=Britannica.com |accessdate=2013-01-27}}</ref> The remnants of these people became the modern [[Assyrian people]] (also known as Chaldo-Assyrians) of Iraq, Iran, south eastern Turkey and northeast Syria.\n*[[Babylonia|Babylonian Empire]]\n*[[Assyria|Assyrian Empire]]\n*[[Ebla]]{{snd}} 23rd century BC\n\n===South Semitic===\n* [[Kingdom of Aksum]]{{snd}} 4th century BC to 7th century AD\n* [[Amhara people]]\n* [[Argobba people]]\n* [[Dahalik language|Dahalik people]]\n* [[Gurage people]]\n* [[Harari people]]\n* [[Mehri people]]\n* [[Old South Arabian]]-speaking peoples\n* [[Sabaeans]] of Yemen{{snd}} 9th to 1st centuries BC\n* [[Silt'e people]]\n* [[Tigrayans|Tigrayan people]]\n* [[Tigre people]]\n* [[Zay people]]\n\n===Unknown===\n* [[Suteans]]{{snd}} 14th century BC\n* [[Thamud]]{{snd}} 2nd to 5th centuries AD\n\n==See also==\n* [[Proto-Semitic language]]\n* [[Middle Bronze Age alphabets]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Additional reference literature==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|first=Martin|last=Baasten|chapter=A Note on the History of 'Semitic'|p=57\u201373|title=Hamlet on a Hill: Semitic and Greek Studies Presented to Professor T. Muraoka on the Occasion of His Sixty-fifth Birthday|publisher=Peeters Publishers|year=2003|isbn=9789042912151|chapter-url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=oIIvqaVaLacC&pg=PA58#v=onepage&q&f=false|ref=harv}}\n* Bennett, Patrick R. 1998. ''Comparative Semitic Linguistics: A Manual''. Eisenbrauns. {{ISBN|1-57506-021-3}}.\n* {{cite book|last = Blau|first = Joshua|title = Phonology and Morphology of Biblical Hebrew|year = 2010|publisher = Eisenbrauns|location= Winona Lake, Indiana|isbn=978-1-57506-129-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Davies|first=John|title=On the Semitic Languages, and their relations with the Indo-European Class. Pt I. On the Nature and Development of Semitic Roots|journal=Transactions of the Philological Society|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.b3924120;view=1up;seq=181|year=1854|issue=10|ref=Davies}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Davies|first=